'''Steve Clarkson''' is an [[American football]] coach. He is considered one of the premier [[quarterback]] coaches.<ref name="USA Today">{{cite news |first=David Leon |last=Moore |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Parents pay dearly to coach kids for stardom |url=http://www.usatoday.com/educate/college/firstyear/casestudies/20040106-coaching.pdf |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher= |date=2002-07-26 |accessdate=2008-02-19 }}</ref> Clarkson has tutored [[Ben Roethlisberger]], [[Matt Leinart]], and [[Jimmy Clausen]], among others.

Clarkson is a 1979 graduate of [[Wilson High School (Los Angeles, California)|L. A. Wilson High School]], where he led his team
to three Los Angeles City Championships with a 39-1 record during three seasons. Clarkson was named to the All-City teams during his Junior and Senior seasons, and was the All-City Player of the Year in 1978 after leading the state in passing yards and total offense. He later was a three-year starter for coach [[Jack Elway]] at [[San Jos<U+00E9> State University]], where he holds several passing records and was named to the Academic All-American teams in 1981 and 1982.

After going undrafted in the [[1983 NFL Draft]], Clarkson played two seasons for the [[CFL]]'s [[Saskatchewan Roughriders]]. He then became a manager for a fast food chain, before turning to football coaching. He founded <U+201C>Air 7<U+201D>, a quarterback academy, that offers tutoring to high school players. Clarkson has since coached more than 20 Division I-A quarterback starters and, including other positions, Air 7 has produced about 80 I-A starters.<ref name="USA Today" />

